    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A <term>matrix</term> is a grid of numbers, which has rows (horizontal groups) and columns (vertical groups). 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        By organising numbers in a grid, we can reveal special patterns that we wouldn't be able to see if we just listed them (like adding to 20 in the example above).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        If a matrix has an equal number of rows and columns, like our example above, we call it a <term>square matrix</term>, since it looks like a square!
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The <term>order</term> (or <term>size/dimension</term>) of a matrix is the number of rows and columns it has. In our example, the order of the matrix was <m>4 \times 4</m>. We always list the number of rows first, then the number of columns.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

